\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
6.1.5
\end_layout

\end_inset

Compute the determinant of the following matrix and determine if it is invertible based on your result:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1 & 1\\
1 & 2 & 3\\
1 & 3 & 6
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
By Sarrus' rule,
 the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det C & =1\cdot2\cdot6+1\cdot3\cdot1+1\cdot1\cdot3-1\cdot3\cdot3-1\cdot1\cdot6-1\cdot2\cdot1\\
 & =12+3+3-9-6-2\\
 & =1,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is nonzero whence 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
6.1.19
\end_layout

\end_inset

For which values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}$
\end_inset

 defined below an invertible matrix?
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{k}=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1 & k\\
1 & k & k\\
k & k & k
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
We find the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}$
\end_inset

 vis Sarrus' rule.
 It is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det A_{k} & =k^{2}+k^{2}+k^{2}-k^{2}-k-k^{3}\\
 & =-k^{3}+2k^{2}-k.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is a cubic polynomial,
 and we wish to find out the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 for which it produces a nonzero number.
 Equivalently,
 we want to find its roots.
 We can factor this polynomial as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det A_{k}=-k(k-1)^{2},
\]

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A_{k}$
\end_inset

 is zero precisely when 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

.
 For these two values,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}$
\end_inset

 is not inverible.
 For all other values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
\end_layout

